it into a dress. fix my old black taffetta to travel in, make a night gown and some Teddy's then I'll be ready. 
I saw Mrs. Garner yesterday she always ask of you. So does Mr. G. and the Balls Dr and Mrs. Mitchel wish to be remember and poor old Mrs. Stoekle still has <unclear/> over you. I'll tell you what! You made quite a bit here altho you were in M social whirl. I always have been so grateful that you got no ticks when you were here. 
I am going to send you a box of persimmons real soon. 
Oh say I'm afraid our rug venture no "nipped in the bud" for a while any way. Mrs. Plumber who does the weaving has been, and is, in very poor health. It may be a little later in the year we can still have them. And I'll see to them-when we can. Mercy I must shut this off. I had such a sweet letter form your mother and received the seeds, my love to you dear girl. Alice M. Neihardt
